Commentary.Commentary: We are set to begin! The players of England stride out to the middle. David Warner and Marcus Harris are the openers for Australia. Chris Woakes will start the proceedings with the ball.

Australia dominated day one thoroughly as their pacers enjoyed bowling in seaming conditions. The lethal trio of Pat Cummins, Josh Hazlewood and Mitchell Starc combined to take 9 wickets while Cameron Green celebrated his maiden Test wicket. The star of the day was the newly made leader, Pat Cummins, a five-fer on his captaincy debut against arch-rivals are stuff to dream of. England will be without their veterans Broad and Anderson. A tough job lies ahead for the other pacers and Joe Root has to lead his troops without his go-to guns. Stay tuned for further updates.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 2 of the first Test match between Australia and England here at Gabba. Australia have had a dream start to the series as they bundled out the visitors for mere 147 runs. The onus is with the Aussies as they will look for a good start to their innings. Overcast conditions and rain might play its role yet again. Let's hope the weather stays clear.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

It was raining non-stop and the umpires had no other option but to call it the day. It was overcast all day but thankfully we got two full sessions of entertaining cricket. The Test era under Cummins is underway and they have done exceptionally well to shred England batting apart. Now Australia will try and build on the advantage they have. But after watching the Aussie pacers, the opposition pacers will be itching to get out. Join us for Day 2 as the action will begin half an hour early at 9.30 am Local (11.30 pm GMT, previous day). Till then, take care and goodbye!

The visitors were 60/5 at one stage and then Pope and Buttler steadied the ship but the latter fell and then wickets started tumbling. England will surely miss Anderson and Broad in this pitch but they have other pacers to bet on.

The pace trio of Mitchell Starc, Josh Hazlewood and Pat Cummins have been right on the money since the word go and the skipper didn't take too long to draw the first blood as he scalped Hameed straightaway after the Lunch break leaving England reeling at 60/5. After that, they were kept quiet for a tad period but Mitchell Starc provided Australia with the breakthrough and then the pacers bossed the game where Cameron Green also bagged his maiden Test wicket and in the end, Pat Cummins ended the innings with a five-fer to his name bundling England out under 150. Australia batters would look to come out and will look to take a healthy first innings lead. For England, there is still enough from the pitch to keep their bowlers interested but remember, they do not have Stuart Broad and James Anderson. The overcast conditions could help Ollie Robinson, Chris Woakes and Mark Wood. Will they able to replicate a performance just like their rivals did? Do join us for the final session at 3 pm local (5 am GMT) to find out.

England already had a herculean task on their hands as they were pushed in early tatters and would have hoped Haseeb Hameed and Ollie Pope to repair the damage work. That wasn't the case though as the former's resistance came to an end in the first over itself after Lunch. The visitors then enjoyed a good passage of play as Jos Buttler played counter-attacking shots to keep the scoreboard moving and not allow the opponent's bowlers to take the game away. Pope supported him well from the other end and just when their partnership was blossoming, came a flurry of wickets and they got bundled out in a blink of an eye.

What a Test captaincy debut for Pat Cummins! First match as a Test captain, in an Ashes opener and has led from the front as he bags a five-wicket haul and the mighty Aussies, have rattled England out for 147 runs. The skipper would be very proud of his team's efforts and will head to the break with nothing but smiles. He leads his side to the pavilion and gets acknowledged by the crowd for his five-fer.

OUT! TAKEN! The captain takes a five-fer. A short ball, on middle. Chris Woakes pulls it but does not middle it. The ball goes off the top edge towards Josh Hazlewood in the deep again. He has to work hard as he runs across from fine leg and takes a diving catch. He plucks it just above the ground. Almost a carbon copy of the catch he took at backward square leg of Pope. Sensational stuff from Josh Hazlewood and England are all out for 147. THAT WILL ALSO BE TEA ON DAY 1!
Commentary.Howout: c Josh Hazlewood b Pat Cummins

Josh Hazlewood is up for a chat. He says that Starc has been pretty good and provided the first breakthrough. Tells that he just tries to bowl on good lengths and that helps him take wickets. Adds that it has been a good start and they bowled in the right areas. Says it is a pretty good wicket and will be a bit harder after lunch. On asked about key to dismiss Joe Root, he says that they just need to bowl good balls and says he is a good player.

Hameed is standing like a wall at one end but the wickets are falling like a pack of cards for England. Burns was out on the very first ball and after that, the floodgates opened for the host as wickets started tumbling. Stokes tried to steady things but he didn't have the return to cricket he wished for. Now, Pope is showing good composure along with Hameed and England will be happy that they have at least steadied the ship and will hope these two continue to build on. Stay tuned with us as the post-lunch session will resume at 12.40 pm local (2.40 am GMT).

It was a good toss to lose for Pat Cummins as after watching that first ball from Mitchell Starc, Australia were more and more thankful for losing the toss. The ball was seaming, shaping both ways and creating all sorts of problems for the visitors. Cummins was shuffling the bowling attack really well and he was certainly enjoying his captaincy role too. A good first session for Australia and they will be very happy heading into the break.

FOUR! Good shot. A length ball, outside off. Ollie Pope drives it through the square on the off side and bags his first boundary.
On a length, on middle. Haseeb Hameed glances it to the fine leg region for a single.
Short of a length, angling across, around off. Haseeb Hameed shoulders arms to it.
A length ball, targeting the pads, hint of seam movement. Haseeb Hameed misses his flick and gets hit on the pads.
Mitchell Starc (4-1-14-1) is back on.
Angles a length ball, on off. Pope defends it confidently.
A length ball, on off. Pope hangs back and blocks it on the off side.
This is short and around off. Ollie Pope ducks under it.
Another outside off delivery, another easy leave for Pope.
A length ball, outside off. Pope covers his stumps and lets it through to the keeper.
A length ball, on middle. Hameed tucks it to square leg for a single.
Fuller in length, on off. Haseeb Hameed wrists it to deep mid-wicket. Long chase for Mitchell Starc who runs from mid on and cuts it off. Three runs taken. 7 runs coming from the over.
On a length, on off. Haseeb Hameed covers the line and blocks it out.
Good-length ball, outside off. No movement there. Haseeb Hameed shoulders arms.
Good-length ball, outside off. Hameed leaves it untouched.
Short of a length, on middle. Ollie Pope pulls it towards deep square leg. Didn't hit it quite from the middle of the bat and the batter gets three runs.
On a good length, on off. Haseeb Hameed defends it awkwardly. The ball goes off the bottom half of the bat towards short fine leg for a single.
Length ball, outside off, shaping away. Left alone. Another maiden for Josh Hazlewood!
Fuller in length this time, on middle. Ollie Pope drives it straight back to the bowler. Josh Hazlewood collects it on his followthrough and gives a stare to the batsman.
Good-length ball, on middle and leg, coming back in. Ollie Pope looks to defend but gets struck on the thigh pad.
Around off, on a length, coming back in. Ollie Pope lets it through.
Length ball, outside off. Ollie Pope leaves it alone.
Back of a length, outside off. Ollie Pope shoulders arms to that one.
Josh Hazlewood is back into the attack. His figures till now read (4-2-2-2).
Short ball, on middle. Haseeb Hameed ducks underneath.
Off the mark straighaway! Full and outside off. Ollie Pope gets forward and pushes it towards covers for a single.

OUT! CAUGHT! Pat Cummins gets rid of the big fish. Hurls in and bowls a back-of-a-length ball, on middle, angling in. Ben Stokes gets all squared up and hops from his crease as he tries to defend. The ball kisses the outside edge and flies to the third slip where Marnus Labuschagne takes a good low catch diving to his left. Ben Stokes is not happy with that and goes back shaking his head off. First wicket for Pat Cummins and Australia well on top! England in deep deep trouble now!
Commentary.Howout: c Marnus Labuschagne b Pat Cummins

Commentary.Commentary: Ollie Pope is the new man in.
WIDE! Cummins bangs in too short, on middle and leg. Ben Stokes sways away from the line. Wide called for height.
On a length, outside off. Ben Stokes taps it to the off side.
FOUR! Well played! Pat Cummins pitches it up, outside off. Ben Stokes leans onto it, opens the face of the bat and drives it through covers for a boundary.
Fuller in length, at 136 kph, on off. Ben Stokes drives it confidently but straight to mid off.

DRINKS! A dominating opening hour for Australia. Their pacers were top-notch from ball one and are very much in a pole position. England though need these two, Stokes and Hameed to stay in the middle and do the repair work.
Fuller this time, on off. Haseeb Hameed puts a stride forward and drives it well but straight to the mid off fielder. A dot to end the over!
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Haseeb Hameed watches it let go past him.
Length ball, outside off. Haseeb Hameed leaves it for the keeper to collect.
What a ripper! Tad fuller, in the fourth stump channel, swinging away. Haseeb Hameed is forced to have a poke at it but gets fortunate as it beats his outside edge.
On a good length, outside off, shaping away. Haseeb Hameed lets it sail through. This is much better line from Starc.
FOUR LEG BYES! Back of a length, on leg. Haseeb Hameed looks to tuck but misses. The ball goes off the thigh pads and races away to the fine leg fence for four leg byes.
On a good length, outside off. Ben Stokes is not troubled by that line as he shoulders arms to that one. A maiden from Pat Cummins!
Good-length ball, on middle. Ben Stokes stays solid in his defence.
On a good length, on middle, angling in. Ben Stokes turns it to short mid-wicket.
Full and outside off, Ben Stokes presses forward and drives it to mid off. Travis Head there does well to dive to his left and stop the ball. Saved a certain boundary.
OH! That was close! Good-length ball, angling in on middle. Ben Stokes lets it go. The ball goes just over the middle stump and carries through to the keeper.
Fuller in length, on the pads. Ben Stokes clips it to short mid-wicket.
Back of a length, outside off. Haseeb Hameed leaves it alone to the keeper.
A length ball, on the hip. Defended out.

A full ball, on middle. Haseeb Hameed drives it straight back. Mitchell Starc seems to get a hand on it as the ball ricochets it on the non-striker's stumps and Australia appeal for a run out but the umpire is not interested in it.
On a length, on off. Haseeb Hameed hops and taps it on the off side.
FOUR! Edgy runs! A full ball, outside off. Haseeb Hameed looks for a big booming drive but gets a thick outside edge over the slip cordon and the ball races away to the third man fence.
A length ball, swinging in, on middle. Haseeb Hameed watches carefully and defends it on the leg side.
Mitchell Starc (2-0-10-1) is back into the attack. He replaces Josh Hazlewood.
A length ball, outside off. Ben Stokes drives it nicely but straight to mid off.
A length ball, on middle. Ben Stokes rocks back and defends it solidly.
Back of a length, on middle, tucked away to mid-wicket.
That one really stayed low. A length ball, angling on off. Ben Stokes looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto his pads.
Full ball, on middle. Ben Stokes covers his stumps and blocks it out.
On a length, on middle. Haseeb Hameed nudges it to deep square leg for one run.
LEG BYE! Short of a length, angling on the thigh pad. Haseeb Hameed misses his flick and gets hit on the pads. The ball rolls to square leg and a leg bye is taken.
Ben Stokes is off the mark. A full ball, on middle, flicked to square leg. He slips as he flicks but no harm done as he completes the run comfortably.
A length ball, outside off. Stokes shuffles across and leaves it alone. Good from Stokes, he just need to stay in the middle for some time.
Another solid defence from Stokes. This is on a length and on middle.
Fuller and on middle. Ben Stokes is strong behind the line of the ball as he defends it out.
Length ball, angling across, outside off. Stokes shoulders arms to it.
Fuller and outside off. Hameed punches it with soft hands through covers and takes a couple of runs.
BEATEN! A full ball, just around the fifth stump channel. Haseeb Hameed looks to defend on the front foot but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Now serves Hameed with a short ball. Haseeb Hameed sits under it.
Full again, on off. Hameed blocks it towards cover.
Fuller ball, on off. Hameed gets on the front foot to keep it out.
JAFFA! Back of a length, outside off. Haseeb Hameed looks to play it but leaves it very late. Good leave actually.
Short of a length, angling across, outside off. Stokes shoulders arms to it.
Ben Stokes walks out to bat at No.5.

OUT! TAKEN! Australia not letting England to settle in. What a start for the Aussies. A full ball, outside off, this one is coming with the angle. Joe Root lunges and looks to block it out but the ball takes the outside edge and it goes straight to the first slip where David Warner holds onto it. England in all sorts of trouble as their skipper goes on a duck.
Commentary.Howout: c David Warner b Josh Hazlewood

Commentary.Commentary: This one nips back in sharply. A length ball, on middle. Root stays back to defend but misses and gets hit high on the pads.
BEATEN! Beauty. A full ball, outside off, this one hits the deck and shapes away. Root prods to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
On a length and angling on middle. Joe Root hops and defends it on the leg side.
A length ball, outside off. Root shoulders arms to it.
Back of a length, on middle. Haseeb Hameed gets on top of the ball and blocks it from the crease.
Full and on middle. Haseeb Hameed watches it closely and meets it with a dead bat.
Slightly fuller, on the off pole. Haseeb Hameed pats it back to the bowler.
Pitched up, outside off, Haseeb Hameed shuffles across a bit before making a leave.
Length ball, on off, coming back in sharply. Haseeb Hameed is caught in the crease as he tries to defend and gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Back of a length, on off. Haseeb Hameed looks to defend but the ball goes off the outside edge and falls short of the man at second slip.
Pat Cummins is into the attack now.
Huge inward movement! Back of a length, on off. The ball rises on that occasion and shaped back in sharply. Joe Root looks to defend but gets hit on the pads. A wicket-maiden from Josh Hazlewood.
Length ball, in the corridor of uncertainty. Joe Root presses forward and steers it to point.
Back of a length, on off, shaping back in again. Joe Root taps it towards covers.
Full and on off, shaping back in. Joe Root plays that one back to the bowler.
The skipper of England, Joe Root walks out to the middle.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Alex Carey takes his first catch on his debut and England lose their second wicket. Josh Hazlewood serves a good-length ball, around off, with a hint of away movement. Enough to kiss the outside edge of Dawid Malan's bat as he has a poke at it. Alex Carey makes no mistake behind the stumps as it was a regulation catch. Dawid Malan has to walk back to the pavilion and Australia are all pumped as they have got two wickets very early into this game.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Carey b Josh Hazlewood

Commentary.Commentary: Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Dawid Malan leaves it for the keeper to collect.
Good-length ball, outside off. Haseeb Hameed shoulders arms to that one.
Starc drags his length a bit this time, outside off, shaping away. Haseeb Hameed lets it go.
FOUR! That's a shot! Pure timing and placement! Fuller in length, on off. Haseeb Hameed gets into the position early and drives it straight down the ground for a boundary.
Length ball, outside off. An easy leave for Haseeb Hameed.
Fuller in length, outside off. Haseeb Hameed leans onto it and drives but finds the cover fielder.
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Haseeb Hameed lets it sal through.
Just the single off the over then! Josh Hazlewood again hurls in a back-of-a-length ball, on middle this time. Dawid Malan stands up on his toes and defends it down the pitch.
Back of a length, in the fourth stump channel, nipping away from the batter. Good bounce and carry as well. Dawid Malan watches the ball closely and makes a leave.
Haseeb Hameed gets off the mark! Good-length ball, on middle. No movement off the ball this time. Haseeb Hameed tucks it behind square on the leg side for a single.
On a length, on off. Haseeb Hameed covers the line and blocks it down with a dead bat.
JAFFA! Back of a length, around off, nipping in. Haseeb Hameed this time tries to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Back of a length, outside off, nipping in. Haseeb Hameed leaves it alone.
Who will bowl from the other end? It is Josh Hazlewood.
A length ball, on middle. Malan stays back and tucks it to square leg.
A length ball, outside off. Malan blocks it to point.
Fuller in length, on off. Malan opens his face of the bat and hits it through point for a couple of runs.
A full ball, on middle. Dawid Malan defends it towards cover.

FOUR! England and Dawid Malan are underway! This is full and around off, hint of away swing. Dawid Malan without any foot movement looks to defend but this goes off the outer half and through the gully region for a boundary.
Dawid Malan walks out at number 3.

OUT! BOWLED! Can you believe it? That's Ashes for you! Mitchell Starc you beauty! He draws first blood and roars. Starc seams in and bowls it full and on leg. Rory Burns shuffles across too far, tries to flick but misses and gets knocked round his legs. There might be hint of late swing as well. This is a dramatic start as it gets. A wicket of the first ball and Australia are delighted. The players are all over Mitchell Starc. Rory Burns has to take the long walk back and goes without troubling the scorers. England certainly didn't hope for this kind of start. An early blow to them. Welcome to the 'Gabba' says Starc.
Commentary.Howout: b Mitchell Starc

Commentary.Commentary: Done with all the pre-match formalities! We are all set for the action now as the players of Australia stride out to the middle. Haseeb Hameed and Rory Burns are the openers of England. Mitchell Starc to start with the ball. Here we go...

Pat Cummins, the skipper of Australia says that it feels great and he can't wait to get things start. Admits that they were going to bat first but were not quite sure about it. Says that the bowlers and batters will get equal assistance. Tells that the boys are really excited and quite relaxed.

Joe Root, the skipper of England, says that they will bat first. Tells that it wasn't a straightforward call with the wet build-up. Mentions that the pitch looks soft underneath and might do a bit more on the second and third day. Informs that leaving Broad out was a difficult decision to make but all the seamers will have their part to play in the series. Tells that they have prepared very well and are ready to go and enjoy the series and make the most of it.
Australia (Playing XI) - David Warner, Marcus Harris, Marnus Labuschagne, Steven Smith, Travis Head, Cameron Green, Alex Carey (WK), Pat Cummins (C), Mitchell Starc, Nathan Lyon, Josh Hazlewood.
England (Playing XI) - Rory Burns, Haseeb Hameed, Dawid Malan, Joe Root (C), Ben Stokes, Ollie Pope, Jos Buttler (WK), Chris Woakes, Ollie Robinson, Mark Wood, Jack Leach.
TOSS - Up goes the coin and it lands in the favour of ENGLAND. They have elected to BAT first.

The weather is arguably set to play the biggest role in the opening Test as there is a forecast of rain everyday and whether the match will produce a result is open to debate. Both sides would be keen to avoid a losing start so a draw seems the best outlook. With all that, let us hope that the rain gods stay away and we get all the action on Day 1. Stay tuned for toss and further updates.

Will Gabba be a fortress?  Well, Australia had not lost a Test at the Gabba for 33 years until India's famous victory in January. But it still has not been a happy hunting ground for the visitors. Their last win at the Gabba came in 1986 and the visitors now would be keen to break that record.

For England, they have announced their 12-man squad. The bitter truth for them is that they have lost 9 out of their last 10 Tests in Australia. England relies too much on Joe Root and they will need other players to step up if they are to gain the urn. They simply can't rely on individual performances. They will have the services of Ben Stokes but he has not played a competitive game of cricket since July and has not played a red-ball game since his last Test in March. However, his class and competitiveness can never be questioned (try forgetting his masterclass at Headingley). It has been announced that James Anderson will miss the first Test to manage his workload, which means Ollie Robinson and Stuart Broad should feature unless there is a surprise. The England Lions will need to find answers to Steven Smith who racked up the bulk of runs in the 2019 Ashes series (774 to be precise) and they would also be aware of Marnus Labuschagne who has been a revelation for Australia. England would be raring to stamp their authority straightaway. The Brits would love to win their first Ashes down under since 2011 and thus, get the urn back to merry-old London.

Australia have already announced their playing 11 and this curtain-raiser marks the new era with Pat Cummins to lead his nation for the first time. He has Steven Smith as his deputy partner and they also have a new man behind the stumps in Alex Carey who will make his Test debut and couldn't have asked for a better platform than this to show his skills. Their batting order looks sorted with David Warner and Marcus Harris as their openers while their middle order relies on two batsmen who are rock solid - Steven Smith and Marnus Labuschagne. On the bowling front, they have the deadly pace trio of Mitchell Starc, Josh Hazlewood and Pat Cummins and in spin, they possess Nathan Lyon. Australia owing to their home record will definitely begin as favorites and will have their eyes wide open to retain the urn.

Well, well, well! The day has finally arrived. Wherever you are, just go home and stick to your television screens because it is time for probably one of the most intense rivalry in the history of cricket. Yup, you guessed it right. It is time for THE ASHES. It hasn't been long since these teams last crossed swords in an Ashes series but yet it feels like an eternity. The last time both sides met, Australia retained the urn although the spoils were shared. Both teams would be eager to step on the field and bring on their 'A' game as one team would start their quest to gain the urn while the other to retain. Who will win the first Test match? Will the weather forecast permit to have a full game? How will Pat Cummins lead his side as a captain? Will England win a Test in Australia after almost 10 years? All these questions will be answered over the course of these five days. On that note, a warm welcome to the coverage of the first day of the Ashes.
... MATCH DAY ...

We are back for England's second innings! Australian players stride out to the middle and take their respective fielding positions. Rory Burns and Haseeb Hameed are the openers for England. Mitchell Starc to start the proceedings with the ball.

So Australia have added another 82 runs to their tally to post a lead of 278. The host had England on the ropes all day long. Starc started the session and played a good innings of 35 and then Lyon chipped in some quick runs while Head continued to blossom on the other end, he scored 150 and carried on to rub more salt on England's wounds. Earlier in the innings, it was the partnership of Warner and Labuschagne that troubled them, both showed good composure but failed to reach the triple-digit score with Warner just missing by 6 runs. Wickets started tumbling down and it looked like England founded their rhythm until Head came out to bat. He was in a different mood as he batted at a good strike rate and just asked the tail-enders to support him from the other end. Things started slipping again for England as they failed to take the remaining three wickets quickly. Lately, England were made to work hard to scalp the wickets and now it is their batters' job to start on a front foot and at least stay compact until the Lunch break.

OUT! BOWLED! Finally, England get their man and end Australia's innings as well. Travis Head makes room for himself very early and exposes his stumps. Mark Wood fires a straight ball, on the stumps. Travis Head tries to carve it over covers but he backed way too far and the ball was out of his reach. It sends the stumps flying and Travis Head walks back to the pavilion on the back of an excellent knock. Australia finish with 425 and have a lead of 278 runs!
Commentary.Howout: b Mark Wood

Commentary.Commentary: DROPPED! That has been the story for England so far! Fuller this time, on middle, another off-pace delivery. Travis Head moves to the off side and flicks it uppishly towards deep mid-wicket. Haseeb Hameed charges ahead to take the catch. Dives in front but palms it out. The batters don't run though as Head wants to face as many deliveries as possible.
Good-length ball, outside off. Took the pace off the ball. Travis Head looks to have a poke at it but drops his bat at the end.
Full ball, outside off. Josh Hazlewood defends off the front foot.
Tossed up, outside off. Hazlewood rocks back and blocks it out.
Full and outside off. Josh Hazlewood prods across and defends it to covers.
Outside off. Head mistimes his sweep to square leg for a quick single.
Full again, outside off. Head tries to sweep but gets an inside edge onto the pads.

FOUR! 150 for Travis Head! What an innings this is from him. He gets all the applause and the Gabba crowd erupts to cheer him. A full ball, on middle. Head slog-sweeps it to deep mid-wicket for a boundary and gets to his 150 in style.
A yorker now, on middle. Josh Hazlewood gets his bat down in time.
Short ball again, on middle. Josh Hazlewood looks to block but gets hit on the gloves. No control on that shot and the ball drops safe on the deck.
Short ball, on middle. Josh Hazlewood ducks under it.
Josh Hazlewood is the last batter to walk in.

OUT! TAKEN! Wood finally gets his man. Short ball, on middle. Lyon looks to pull but gets a leading edge high in the air and towards short square leg. Ollie Robinson charges in and takes a simple catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Ollie Robinson b Mark Wood

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Edgy runs! Short of a length, on middle. Lyon rocks back and looks to pull but top-edges it over the keeper's head for a boundary.
In the air but safe. A length ball, on the pads. Head hops and flicks it uppishly and towards deep square leg for a single.
A loopy ball, on middle. Lyon pushes it to mid-wicket.
Darted on the pads, this is flicked to square leg for a single.
Around off, pushed to covers.
Quicker now, spinning back in. Head blocks it out.
Flatter and outside off. Lyon dabs it late past the first slip for a single.
A full ball, on middle, pushed to mid on.

DRINKS! Travis Head is inching closer to 150 now and Australia have a massive lead of 266 runs. England bowlers already look tired and are getting no help from the pitch as well. They will look to quickly scalp the remaining two wickets and stop Australia to have a lead past 300. Bowling change for England. Spin for the first time today. Jack Leach (11-0-95-1) comes into the attack.
SIX! Just over the fielder! A length ball, angling on the pads. Head whips it away and just clears the square leg fielder for a biggie. 5 runs shy of 150.
Short of a length, on middle. Lyon swivel-pulls it through mid-wicket for three runs.
On a length, on off. Head hops and taps it to cover for a single.
Third time missed. Length and down the leg side, this was close to the leg pole. Head shuffles way across and misses his tuck.
Length again and down the leg side. Head steps across and misses his flick.
Short and down the leg side. Head misses his flick.
Mark Wood is brought back into the attack. He replaces Ben Stokes.
Mark Wood is brought back into the attack. He replaces Ben Stokes.
Good-length ball, outside off. Lyon lets it sail through.
Length ball, on middle. Lyon tucks it on the leg side.
Fuller, on off. Driven towards mid off.
Good-length ball, angling in. Lyon knocks it back to the bowler.
On a length, on middle. Flicked to deep square leg for a brace.
Short of a length, on middle. Pulled to deep square leg for a single.
Fuller in length, on middle. Lyon drives it back to the bowler.
Back of a length, on middle and leg. Lyon again tries to pull. He misses and gets hit on the thigh pad.

FOUR! Lyon takes on Stokes! Enough with the short balls, he says! Short of a length, on middle. Nathan Lyon pulls it to deep mid-wicket. Off the bottom of the bat but enough to clear the ropes. 400 up for Australia!
Short of a length, on middle. Lyon tries to pull but misses.
Length ball, down leg. Head tickles it to deep backward square leg for a single.
Length ball, on middle. Head tucks it on the leg side.
Good-length ball, on middle and leg. Lyon looks to play across but gets hit on the pads. England appeal for an lbw but the umpire says no. Going down leg.
DROPPED! Fuller in length, outside off, nipping away. Nathan Lyon chips it to the left of Woakes. He extends his left hand and tries to catch it but the ball fails to stick in his palms.
On a good length, outside off. Lyon leaves it alone.
Back of a length, outside off. That bounced sharply. Lyon looks to drive but misses.
On a length, on off. Lyon pushes it to mid off.
Length ball, on leg. Head tries to defend but gets hit on the pads. The ball drops on the leg side and the batters take a leg bye.
Length ball, on off. Lyon stays back and nudges it to mid on.
And again! A short ball, down leg. Lyon looks to pull but once again fails to make any connection.
Another bouncer, on middle. Nathan Lyon looks to pull but misses.
JUST SHORT! Short ball, on leg. Travis Head pulls it without any timing to deep square leg. Haseeb Hameed charges ahead from the deep to take the catch but the ball falls just short of him.
Back of a length, on middle. Lyon hops and tucks it to square leg. Gets off the mark with a single but more importantly, hands over the strike to Head.
Good effort ball from Stokes! Serves a bumper, on off. Steep bounce on that occasion! Travis Head hops and takes his eyes off the ball. The ball goes off the outside edge to third man for a single.
Nathan Lyon walks out now.

OUT! CAUGHT! Finally, England get the breakthrough! Woakes hurls a length ball, on middle. Mitchell Starc flicks it towards deep square leg. Gets the height but not the distance. Rory Burns is stationed over there. He doesn't even have to move an inch. Keeps his eyes on the ball and takes it with ease. Mitchell Starc departs but Australia will feel he has done his job. Chris Woakes breaks the 85-run stand and now England will look to wrap things up.
Commentary.Howout: c Rory Burns b Chris Woakes

Commentary.Commentary: Length ball, outside off. Starc lets it be.
FOUR! Starc is playing a gem of an innings here! Length ball, on middle. Mitchell Starc lofts it over mid on to fetch himself a boundary.
On a length, on leg. Starc defends it out from the crease.
Good-length ball, outside off. Starc has a feel for it. The ball zips past the outside edge.
Short of a length, around off. Head stays back and steers it to backward point for a single.
Change from both ends! Chris Woakes (22-7-68-1) is brought back into the attack.
Another solid defense from Starc. 7 coming off it, an expensive start from Stokes.
On a length, on off. Starc blocks this one on the deck.
Short and on middle, pulled away to square leg for a single.
Short of a length, on middle. Head has to get on his toes to keep this one out.
SIX! Statement from Head! A full ball, on middle. Head smashes it straight down the ground for a biggie.
Length ball, angling on middle, pushed back to the bowler.
Ben Stokes (9-0-50-0) is brought into the attack.
On middle. Blocked out.
FOUR! Good shot! Pitches this one up, on middle. Starc drives it firmly through mid on for a boundary.
A length ball, on middle. Starc is solid on his defense.
Short now, down leg. Easy leave for Starc.
A low dipping full toss, on middle. Starc jams it out on the off side.
A length ball, on middle. Starc defends it off the front foot.
Short of a length, on middle. Head hops and blocks it out.
On middle, tucked away to mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! More runs! A length ball, outside off. Starc gets an outside edge and the ball rolls away through the gully region for a boundary. It went through the diving fielder.
Length and angling on the pads. Head flicks it aerially and towards fine leg for a single.
A short of a length, outside off. Head hops and taps it to third man for a brace. Easy for Australia, no trouble whatsoever.
Short of a length, outside off, extra bounce as well. Head has a poke at it and misses it completely. Gets beaten on the outside edge.
A length ball, outside off, this one nips back in. Starc looks to defend away from the body but gets beaten on the inside edge.
On the pads, this is flicked to square leg.
A length ball, outside off. Starc lifts it towards mid off who collects it on a bounce.
A length ball, on off. Head dabs it to deep point for a single.
A length ball, outside off, this one stays low and is too close for Head to cut it, misses.
A length ball, on off. Head blocks it to covers.
A length ball, on middle. Starc stays back and pushes it to Wood.
Short stuff from Wood. Starc sits under it.
On middle, on a length, hit back to the bowler.
Short of a length, on middle. Starc misses his flick as he closes his bat face early. Gets hit high on the pads.
A length ball, angling on the pads. Starc tucks it to deep square leg and collects a couple of runs.
A length ball, outside off. Starc taps it to point.
Back of a length, on off. Head jumps and defends it out off the inner half of the bat.
Short of a length, on middle. Head pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a brace.
Good-length ball, angling away from off. Travis Head has a poke at it. The ball beats the outside edge and carries through to the keeper.
Good-length ball, attacking the stumps. Head covers the line and defends it back to the bowler.
Short ball from Robinson, on middle. Head ducks under it and evades it comfortably.
Touch fuller, outside off. Head leaves it for the keeper to collect.
Back of a length, on off. Starc hops and knocks it back to the bowler. These two are looking very solid!
Fuller this time, on off. Starc drives it through cover-point for a couple of runs.
On a length, on middle, at 145 kph. Starc defends it on the leg side.
On a length, on off. Starc defends it with ease.
Back of a length, outside off, at 141 kph. Head slashes it to deep point for a run.
Mark Wood (20-4-57-1) is into the attack now.
Back of a length, on off. Head hops and taps it to point.
Length ball, on leg. Starc pushes it to mid on.
Length ball, outside off. Head dabs it past gully for a single.
Back of a length, on middle. Head blocks it from the crease.
Full and outside off. Head drives it towards covers.
Length ball, on middle. Head blocks it on the leg side.
Good-length ball, outside off. Head leaves it alone.
Back of a length, on middle. Starc looks to defend. The ball goes off the outside edge to point.
Short of a length, outside off. Starc leaves it alone.
FOUR! Great shot! Fuller, on middle and leg. Starc works it away to wide of mid on for a boundary.
Short of a length, on leg. Head looks to tuck. The ball goes off the thigh pad to the right of the keeper. The batters take a leg bye.
FOUR! He is continuing from where he left off! Short of a length, on middle. Head pulls it with disdain to deep square leg for a boundary.
Outside off, on a length. Left alone.
Pitched up, outside off. Head pushes it to point. Haseeb Hameed has a wild throw at the stumps for no reason. There is no one backing up and the batters take a single off the overthrows.
Fuller, on off. Starc chips it towards mid off for a single.
On a good length, on off. Starc taps it to point.
Good-length ball, around off, nipping away. Mitchell Starc looks to flick but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Back of a length, on off. Starc taps it on the off side.
Good-length ball, angling away outside off. Starc lets it be.
Who will start from the other end? It is Ollie Robinson.
Fuller, outside off. Head drives it towards covers.
Length ball, on middle. Starc knocks it off the inside portion of the bat to deep square leg. Three taken. Australia now lead by 200 runs!
On a good length, outside off. Starc lets it go.
Good-length ball, outside off. Starc leaves it alone. No signs of any swing as of now.
Short of a length, on middle. Head hops and tucks it to square leg for a single.
Back of a length, on middle. Head stands up on his toes and plays it to gully.
We are all set. The players of England stride out to the middle. Travis Head and Mitchell Starc to continue their innings. Chris Woakes to start with the ball.

Australia have completely bossed the game so far. On Day 1 their bowlers did their job by folding England for a paltry score of 147 and on Day 2 their batters did their job with David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne both scoring half centuries although got to feel for Warner who missed out on a ton by just 6 runs. Later, it was Travis Head who scored runs aggressively and reached the milestone off just 85 balls which is also the fastest Test century at The Gabba. It was a spirited performance from the England's front three pacers but only if they had taken every opportunity which came in their way, the side would have been in a much better position. The Brits will now look to wrap things up and come out to bat with a much more positive intent but will still need a herculean task to get out of this rut.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 3 of the first Test match of the Ashes. Australia are in a commanding position now extending their lead to 196 and still have 3 wickets in hand but more importantly, have Travis Head at the crease who brought up his first Ashes ton. Australia will look to pile as many runs as possible and put England completely out of the contest as there is still ample of time to get a result unless rain plays a spoilsport. Stay tuned for further updates.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Right then! Yet another dominating performance from Australia and they end the second day on a high. They lead by 196 runs and will look to add as many runs as possible while England will look to take those last three wickets quickly. Join us for Day 3 as the action will begin at 9.30 am Local (11.30 pm GMT, previous day). Till then, take care and goodbye!

David Warner is up for a chat, he says that England bowled really well and they were relentless. Tells that how incredible innings it was from Head. Says it was a tight battle between Khawaja and Head and Head got the nod and then scored a brilliant century. Tells that one doesn't know if it will be their last day or not so one has to go out, enjoy and make the most out of it. Mentions that when you are out of runs, you need some luck and he got exactly that.

England were in a good position but Head's brilliant batting took the game away from them. They have to blame themselves, misfields, drop catches, run out chances. Opportunities were there but all went begging. First, it was the partnership between Warner and Labuschagne and then once they fell, Head came out of nowhere and made things from bad to worse. Everyone were looking tired, bowlers, fielders and even Root, who had no clue what to do and get back into the game.

David Warner started the day with Marnus Labuschagne walking out later on the other end and the duo did really well to play the first session with great composure but Labuschagne fell just after posting a partnership in excess of 150. After that, wickets started tumbling and even Warner missed out on his century. It was then, Travis Head who was looking so good in the middle, just wanted someone to stay at the other end as he was scoring the bulk of runs. The tail-enders did really well to help him reach the landmark as he brought up his first Ashes century.

Absolutely wonderful innings from Travis Head, scoring his first Ashes hundred, stuff to dream of. Australia in pole position as they end the day with a lead of 196 runs and looks like they are not yet done. Travis Head walks off to a standing ovasion from the Gabba crowd and his teammates as well and he has righly deserved so.
Fuller and wider, outside off. Starc lets it go. THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 2!
Length ball, outside off. Starc shoulders arms.

Was there an inside edge there? Definitely some sound when the ball passed the bat. Good-length ball, on off, coming back in. Mitchell Starc has a swing at it but misses. The ball goes well away from the keeper and Jos Buttler does really well to dive to his right but fails to pouch it. Yup! HotSpot shows that there was an inside edge there.

Good-length ball, on middle and leg. Starc looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads. Mark Wood appeals for an lbw but the umpire says no. He is interested but Joe Root does not opt for a review.
Outside off, left alone.

Full and on the pads. Head flicks it to deep mid-wicket. Jack Leach from deep square leg chases it and keeps it down to three runs. The England players look very tired now and there body language says it all.
Full and outside off. Starc lets it sail through.
Outside off, left alone by Starc.
Fuller in length, on off. Driven to mid off.
On a length, on leg. Tucked on the leg side for a single.
Fuller in length, on middle. Head drills it to mid on.
Short of a length, on middle. Head pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Fuller in length, on leg. Starc misses his flick. Gets hit on the pads. Wood with an half-hearted appeal for an lbw but the umpire is unmoved. That was going down the leg side.
On a length, on middle. Blocked out.
THICK EDGE AND FOUR! Good-length ball, outside off. Starc looks to drive. The ball goes off the outside edge past the diving backward point fielder for a boundary.
Back of a length, on off. Head pushes it towards covers for a single.
Fuller in length, on middle. Pushed back to the bowler.
Length ball, on leg. Head looks to work it away but gets hit on the thigh pad.
The physios come running in the ground as Travis Head gets hit near the chin. Wood walks straight to him to apologize though. He ssems fine now and we are ready to resume.

OH DEAR! NASTY! Wood steams in and bowls a full toss, on middle, at 138.6 kph. Travis Head is completely taken aback by the bounce and is in no position to play that shot. The ball hits the gloves and then rolls up to hit his chin. He immediately goes down on the ground. Mark Wood walks up to him to see if he is okay. He looks to be in some pain though. Also, Mark Wood has overstepped and no ball has been given.
A length ball, outside off. Head looks to defend but it takes the outside edge through the gully region and three runs are taken as the fielder chases it back and cuts it off.
Full and on middle. Starc looks to go big down the ground but ends up slicing it over covers for three runs.
A length ball, outside off. Starc shoulders arms.
Short of a length, on the hips, Head flicks it on the leg side. Woakes runs across and collects it. A single.

FOUR! There it comes! FIRST ASHES HUNDRED FOR TRAVIS HEAD! What a knock this has been from him. Fuller in length, on middle and leg. Travis Head drives it past the diving mid on fielder and the ball races away to the boundary. He removes his helmet and soaks applause from his dressing room and the crowd erupts as well. Gets a hug from Mitchell Starc. He is elated. There were many questions regarding his place but he has repaid it by this ton. Sensational batting!
A length ball, outside off, shaping away as well. Left alone.
Second new ball is available now. Will England take it? Yes, they have opted to take it and it is Chris Woakes who will steam in now.
Fired in, on leg. Starc looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads. An appeal for an lbw but the umpire says no. Going down leg.
On middle, pushed back to the bowler.
Full and on middle. Head eases it down to long on for a single.

Loopy ball, on middle. Travis Head looks to work it on the leg side. He gets hit on the forearm and the ball lobs up in the air behind the keeper on the leg side. Rory Burns moves to his right and dives forward to take the catch but it didn't come off the gloves.
This is pushed back to the bowler.
Short and on off. Head punches it to wide of deep mid-wicket. The fielder moves to his right and cuts it off. Keeps it down to two runs.

Short of a length, on middle. Travis Head hops and taps it towards covers. He wanted to be on strike the next over and thus sprins across for a quick single. Haseeb Hameed has a shy at the striker's end but misses. Good running!
Short ball, on off. Starc takes his eyes off the ball and pulls it without any timing to mid-wicket. A single is taken.
On a good length, on middle. Starc pushes it to cover.
Good-length ball, outside off. Starc with an another leave.
Back of a length, outside off. Starc watches the ball closely and lets it go.
Length ball, on off. Head pushes it through covers for a single.
Slightly short outside off. Starc taps it to point.
Full and on middle. Starc pushes it to covers.
Tossed up, on off, pushed to covers.
A low full toss, Head drives it to deep cover. Malan there runs across and dives but fumbles to collect it but does enough to flick it back with his leg. Three.
Tossed up, outside off. Head looks to slog-sweep but gets a top edge over the keeper's head and they take two runs.
Full ball, on off. Starc gets low and pushes it on the off side for a single.

Interesting thoughts from Shane Warne on air. He reckons that with not much batting left, Australia should look to declare and take a few English wickets tonight. That means Head will have to try and get to his century quickly.
Immediately off the mark! Length ball, on off. Starc nudges it to mid-wicket for a single.
Full and on middle, drilled down to long off for a single.
Short and on middle. Head ducks under it.
Short of a length, on off. Head again gets cramp for room as he looks to cut.
Short and on middle. Head sits under it.
Short of a length, around off. Head looks to cut but gets cramp for room and misses.
The new batter in is Mitchell Starc.

OUT! TAKEN! Australia 7 down now. A full ball, down the leg side. Pat Cummins flicks it late with soft hands towards the leg slip where Haseeb Hameed is stationed and he takes a good low catch. Pat Cummins is disappointed with himself as he walks back. The England skipper gets the opponent skipper! End of a crucial 70-run stand.
Commentary.Howout: c Haseeb Hameed b Joe Root

Commentary.Commentary: Follows Cummins on the leg side and serves it full, pushed back to the bowler.
A loopy ball now. Head works it to deep cover for a single.
Short and outside off, cut away to covers for a brace.
Three taken! Full ball, outside off. Pat Cummins makes room and gets low, lifts this one over covers for three runs.
Full ball, on off. Head skips down and pushes it to long off for a single. 300 up for Australia!
Back of a length, on middle and leg. Travis Head is taken aback by the bounce. He does well though to drop it to the off side and take a single. 10 runs off the over.
FOUR! Top edge and the ball rolls away to the fence! A short ball, on middle. Head looks to pull but gets a top edge and races away behind the keeper for a boundary.
FOUR! A length ball, on middle. Head smashes it wide of mid on and bags a boundary for himself.
NO BALL! A length ball, angling on middle. Head misses his flick and gets hit high on the pads. Ben Stokes oversteps and the umpire signals a no ball.
Short ball, on off. Head sits under it.
On a length, on middle. Head punches it to covers.
Full and on middle. Head pushes it to mid on.
Ben Stokes (6-0-35-0) is back into the attack.
Flatter and angling on middle. Cummins lunges and blocks it out.

FIVE RUNS! Oh dear! Full and outside off. Head comes down the track and smashes it to mid off for a single. Ben Stokes collects the ball and has a shy at the keeper's end. Pat Cummins makes his ground with a dive. The throw is a wild one and it goes past Jos Buttler and dribbles away into the fence. Jack Leach is not happy with that at all.
SIX! MASSIVE! Tosses it up, on middle. Travis Head comes down the track and hammers it over the bowler's head for a biggie.
On off, punched to mid off for a single.
Loopy ball, on off. Pat Cummins puts a big stride forward to defend. The ball goes off the outside edge to third man. Haseeb Hameed gives it a chase and cuts it off. Two taken.
Loopy ball, outside off. Head punches it to deep point off the back foot for a single. Much better line from Leach!
Down the leg side. Cummins looks to flick but misses.
Fuller, on middle. Cummins flicks it to deep square leg for a couple of runs.
Length ball, on middle and leg. Cummins pushes it to mid on.
Length ball, on middle and leg. Cummins looks to heave it away but gets hit on the thigh pads. A muted appeal for an lbw from the keeper but the umpire says no.
Full again, on off, little slower this time. Cummins pushes it on the off side.
Fuller in length, outside off. Cummins drives it firmly but straight to the cover fielder.

8 overs to go now, for the second new ball. Australia lead by 125 and if they go wicketless for the next 8 overs, in all likelihood, that lead will cross 150, which is a lot on this surface. The second new ball will be very crucial but England need to hold on too, till that period. They have missed quite a few opportunities and Australia have capitalized. Also, a bowling change for England. Ollie Robinson comes back on.

FOUR! Full and down the leg side. Head gets on his knee and sweeps it past the leg slip for a boundary. Poor ball but England will not mind that too much. They need Cummins to face Wood and try and take wickets.

MISFIELD, FOUR! Oopsy, what happened there? Short, around leg, Head pulls it to deep backward square leg. There are shouts of 'CATCH IT!' but Haseeb Hameed over there does not spot the ball at all. He looks to his left, then his right and in the end, realizes that the ball is coming at him. Runs forward but the ball bounces in front of him and worse, hits his body and deflects behind. It lobs in the air and Hameed looks to stop it off the rebound but too late, the ball is beyond the ropes! Oh dear, that is right in front of a vocal 'Gabba crowd and it is cheering!
On middle, pushed back to the bowler.
Full and on middle. Head leans and wrists it to the leg side.
Tossed up, on middle, eased down to long on for a single.
Flatter and on middle. Head nudges it to square leg and takes an easy single.
Angles a length ball, on middle, tucked to square leg.
A length ball, outside off. Cummins looks to defend but gets an outside edge and the ball rolls along the ground to the slip fielder.
Serves a pacy bouncer on middle. Cummins sits under it.
Short of a length, outside off. Cummins watchfully leaves it.
On a length, on off. Head taps it to the gully region where the fielder fumbles and allows a single.
FOUR! FIFTY for Travis Head, his 8th Test fifty and he is controlling the innings well really well. A full toss, on off. Head drives it firmly and through covers for a boundary.
Drifting it on leg, Cummins is solid in his defence.
Drags his length back and bowls it on leg, Travis Head works it to backward square leg for a single.

FOUR! Edgy! Loopy ball, on middle. Travis Head steps out and looks to cut. The ball goes off the outside edge and goes past the keeper's gloves to third man for a boundary. Moves onto 46 now! Bit strange from Root and Leach. They have a leg slip for Head but no conventional slip. Had that conventional slip been there, it would have gone straight to him. Possibly because Leach has been expensive, it has forced Root to go defensive and it has cost them a potential wicket. That too, of the last recognized batter.
Floats it up, on leg. Travis Head tucks it on the leg side.
Good shot for three! Tossed up, on middle. Pat Cummins lifts it over covers. Long chase for the cover fielder and the batters take three runs.
Loopy ball, on middle. Cummins presses forward and defends it out.
Jack Leach (8-0-62-1) is back into the attack. Good time for him to make a comeback. Australia have not allowed him to settle at all.

Expected ploy from Wood and England. After that blow to Head on his elbow before Drinks, the visitors are now aiming a barricade of short stuff to the former Aussie Test vice captain. There is a leg gully in place as well and the plan is to keep Head in his crease and then perhaps, slip in a full ball or two, in the hope that Head does not move his feet and nicks it behind.
Fuller in length, pushed wider. Travis Head latches on it and drives it through cover-point for an easy two.
On middle, Head pushes it to mid on.
Back of a length again, on off. Head hops and fends it away to the off side. Wood looking tired now!
FOUR! Head moves into the 40s! A full ball, outside off. Head slashes it hard and through the point region for a boundary. A little bit of the late Phillip Hughes in that shot.
Back of a length, outside off. Head jumps up on his toes and blocks it out.
Short of a length, outside off. Head punches it to mid off.
Loopy ball, on middle. Head eases it down to long on for a single.
On middle. Head rocks back and looks to defend. Gets an inside edge and the ball rolls on the leg side.
Tossed up, on middle. Pushed back to the bowler.
Outside off, cut away to point.
Full and on off. Head prods and smashes it back to the bowler. Root collects it and mimes a throw at him.
Loopy ball, outside off. Head cuts it through point for a couple of runs.

DRINKS! Travis Head calls the physio straightaway after getting hit on the back elbow. Still looks in a bit of pain as he gets assessed by the physio. A good passage of play for both the teams. Australia now lead by 93 runs while England will be looking to take that four wickets quickly. Around 90 minutes roughly remaining to bowl out 31 overs. So plenty of time for both teams to cause some damage. It has been a very hot and humid day, so both teams are taking their time to get started. The umpires are not too concerned and rightly so.
Back of a length, on middle. Tucked to backward square leg for a single.
Back of a length, on off. Head hops and looks to defend but misses. He gets hit right above the elbow and looks to be in some pain.
Good-length ball, on off. Head defends it from the crease.
Fuller in length, around off. Head doesn't move his feet much and looks for a drive. Only manages to get an inside edge onto the pads.
A bouncer this time, on middle and leg. Head sits under it.
Good-length ball, on middle. Head covers the line and knocks it back to the bowler with a straight bat.
Mark Wood (15-4-36-1) is back into the attack.
Loopy ball down leg yet again. Cummins leaves it untouched.
Again down the leg side. Cummins pads it away this time.
Down the leg side, turning away. Cummins lets it be.
Fuller this time, on the pads. Cummins blocks it out on the leg side.
Loopy ball, on leg. Cummins tucks it on the leg side.
Short and outside off, Head rocks back and scythes it through cover-point for three runs.
Full again, angling on middle. Pat Cummins nudges it on the leg side. A successful over from Chris Woakes, wicket-maiden over.
Welcomes Cummins with a fuller ball, on middle. Cummins defends it out.
The skipper, Pat Cummins walks out to bat.

OUT! TAKEN! England finds another breakthrough and Carey's debut innings is cut short for a timid score. Short of a length, on middle. Alex Carey gets on his toes as he looks to wrists it to mid-wicket but finds Ollie Pope at short mid-wicket who shows good reflexes and grabs this one over his head. Australia lead by 89 runs and England hanging in there.
Commentary.Howout: c Ollie Pope b Chris Woakes

Commentary.Commentary: Full and outside off. Carey prods across and shoulders arms to it.
Angles a length ball, on middle. Carey gets on the front foot and defends it out.
On a length, on middle. Blocked out.
SIX! BANG! A loopy ball, outside off. Head tonks it all the way over long on for a biggie.
Around off, pushed to covers.
A full ball, angling around leg. Alex Carey tries to reverse sweep it to the fine leg region for a single. Buttler puts up an appeal for LBW but that came off the blade.
Again pushes it but straight to covers. Dot.
Tossed up, on off, Carey drives it to covers.
Starts with a very full ball, on off, pushed down to long off for a single.

Just a bit of a personal opinion. First up, hats off to Ben Stokes for bowling even with so much discomfort. One can clearly see him in pain, and one would assume that he has been on the field just so that he is not stripped off his batting position for not spending enough time on the field. But one also needs to remember that this is just the first match of a massive 5-Test series. Should Joe Root just look after Stokes' health a little bit more? Yes, England need wickets right now, but in that process, they might end up sacrificing one of the world's greatest allrounders. Remember Ashes 2019, where Root overworked Jofra Archer and the result was a spate of injuries? Food for thought. Joe Root does take Ben Stokes off the attack and introduces himself to bowl. Good call this from the skipper.
Three taken! A short ball, outside off. Carey slashes onto it, not quite off the middle towards deep cover and the batters take three runs.
Pitches it up, on off. Head pushes it more off the outer half of the bat towards cover-point for a single.
Length again, on middle. Carey tucks it to mid-wicket and takes a single.
On a length, on middle. Carey solidly blocks it out.
Short of a length, on middle. Carey looks to flick but gets hit on the gloves. The ball lobs and drops back on the deck.
A length ball, outside off. Carey lets it through to the keeper.

FOUR! Third boundary of the over! On a length, on middle. Head pulls it to deep square leg. Jack Leach runs across to his right, puts a dive and flicks it but the ball rolls back and touches the fence.
Length ball, outside off. Punched to covers.
Short of a length, on middle. Head defends it on the leg side.
FOUR! Now through the off side. A length ball, outside off. Head cuts it through point for another boundary. Turning out to be a good over for Australia.
FOUR! Pulled away! Short of a length, on middle. Head hangs back and pulls it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Short of a length, on middle. Head gets on his toes as he tucks it to mid-wicket.
Ben Stokes (5-0-23-0) is back into the attack. Will bowl off a shorter run-up than his usual. Probaly because he is feeling some discomfort around his knee area.
Just short of the third fielder. A length ball, outside off. Carey looks to push but gets an outside edge to the third slip where the fielder dives forward and collects it on a bounce.
A length ball, on middle. Carey works it to mid-wicket.
On a length, on middle. Carey blocks it out.
Length again, outside off. Carey leaves it alone to the keeper.
Swing and a miss! A length ball, outside off. Carey looks to cut but fails to get any bat on it.
A length ball, angling across, outside off. Carey shoulders arms to it.

The on-air commentators inform us that Cameron Green has been dismissed 4 times in First-Class cricket, SHOULDERING ARMS. The great Ian Chappell would have said, "Kid, you have been given a bat to play. USE IT!"

FOUR RUNNING RUNS! Robinson sprays this one on the pads, Travis Head flicks it through mid-wicket. The mid-wicket fielder gives it a long chase and prevents the ball racing away to the boundary but the batters have run four already.
And again! Carey drives this full ball again to long off. The mid off fielder gives it a chase and manages to keep it down to three runs.
FOUR! First runs for Alex Carey in Test cricket! Opens his account with a boundary. This was full, on off. Alex Carey drives it towards long off for a boundary.
Fuller, on the pads. Carey nudges it to square leg.
Touch fuller, outside off, angling away. Carey shoulders arms to that one.
Well blocked! Good-length ball, angling across. Carey presses forward and knocks it back to the bowler.
On a good length, on middle. Head stands up on his toes and defends it back to the bowler.
Short of a length, on off. Head pushes it to point and shouts 'no run'.
Length ball, outside off. Head taps it towards covers.
Good-length ball, on middle. Head defends it with a dead bat.
Good-length ball, on off, nipping away. Travis Head looks to defend but misses. The ball whistles past the outside edge and carries through to the keeper.
Back of a length, on middle. Head defends it out off the front foot.
Chris Woakes (14-4-37-0) is back into the attack.
Slower ball, on the pads. Head flicks it to mid-wicket and takes a quick single.
A length ball, on middle. Travis Head stays back and defends it out.
Good-length ball, on off. Head tries to leave it alone but is late in lifting his bat. The ball goes off the bottom edge and drops on the ground.
Good-length ball, on off. Head gets all squared up and manages a thick outside edge to the fifth slip fielder.
Fuller this time, on off. Head presses forward and defends it on the leg side.

FOUR! EDGY! Good-length ball, on middle and leg. Travis Head looks to work it on the leg side but closes the face of the bat too early. The ball goes off the outside edge and goes past the slip cordon and gully for a boundary. Travis Head is very fortunate there. Five slips and a gully and the ball still finds the gap!
Length ball, on off. Carey stays solid in his defence.
Back of a length, on middle. Carey covers his sticks and defends it from the crease.
Short of a length, on middle. Alex Carey negotiates with it well by swaying away from the line.
On a good length, on middle. Carey blocks it from the crease.
Good-length ball, on middle. Alex Carey tries to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Length ball, outside off. Carey throws the kitchen sink at it but fails to connect.
Back of a length, on middle. Head defends it onto the deck. Superb over from Ollie Robinson!
Back of a length, on leg. Carey deflects it off his pads to fine leg for a leg bye.
No hat-trick for Ollie Robinson! Length ball, on middle. Carey blocks it out.

OUT! TIMBER! Sensational stuff from Ollie Robinson and England are back in the contest. Serves a good-length ball, on off, coming back in. Cameron Green comes forward and just shoulders arms to that one. Probably didn't read the length well. The ball jags back in and shatters the stumps. That was not a good leave at all. England are all pumped up and Ollie Robinson is on a hat-trick now. Alex Carey is the new batsman in.
Commentary.Howout: b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Cameron Green is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Would you believe it? Warner misses out on a century. Robinson hurls in and bowls a slower ball, on middle. The ball stops a bit on the surface. David Warner tries to push it towards covers but throws his hands too early. He chips it instead towards extra cover where Ben Stokes dives ahead to catch the ball. Devastation for David Warner as he walks back to the pavilion after an excellent knock. For the first time in seven occasions, David Warner failed to hit a century after being dismissed off a no ball in a Test innings.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Stokes b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, on middle. Warner pushes it back to the bowler.
Length ball, on leg. Warner looks to tuck but misses. Gets hit on the pads and the ball rolls to fine leg. The batters take a leg bye.
Length ball, on off. Head taps it towards covers and scampers across to get off the mark.
Back of a length yet again, on middle. Head jumps and fends it on the leg side this time. Mark Wood falls on his followthrough but is fine to continue.
Back of a length again, on middle. Head hops and blocks it out.

England created a couple of chances but were let down by the sloppiness in the field. First, Rory Burns dropped Warner and then Haseeb Hameed missed a run out chance. The seamers tried everything and toiled hard but couldn't get the breakthrough. Although, Jack Leach remained expensive throughout, it was him who got England that one wicket they were searching for and then Mark Wood got the wicket of the big gun - Steven Smith, which he thoroughly deserved for his probing line and lengths. The wickets remain key for them to keep the deficit as low as possible and first would be targeting David Warner who is inching closer to his century. Join us at 3 pm local (5 am GMT, next day) for the final session.

Post Lunch, runs came very easily for the hosts! David Warner who was bowled off a no-ball in the morning session, rode his luck again as he was given two more reprieves. He got to his 31st Test fifty and Marnus Labuschagne from the other end continued to tick along and the runs kept flowing for them. Later, Marnus Labuschagne tried to attack Jack Leach on each and every ball and in the process holed out. While David Warner continued on his merry way, Steven Smith had a very scratchy stay and departed early. Australia now lead by 46 runs and still have 7 wickets in hand to post a hefty lead.
Some respite for England as they have removed the two big fish - Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith and look to crawl their way back into the game.

England needed an early breakthrough and Ollie Robinson provided them with one removing Marcus Harris early into the game. Robinson continued to create problems for the Aussies with his line and lengths while Mark Wood bowled with some serious pace but to no success. Later, Ben Stokes knocked David Warner in his very first over but he overstepped that delivery. All that hard work England did in the first hour vaporized quickly as David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne started scoring runs at a brisk pace as the pitch eased out. England need to find answers to Australian batters if they are to avoid a huge first innings lead. Join us at 12.40 pm local (2.40 am GMT, next day) for the second session.

Australia didn't have the dream start they would have hoped for as Marcus Harris departed early. But David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne batted very cautiously and kept motoring along well. David Warner was lucky to get a lifeline as he got bowled off a no ball. The duo then continued to keep the scoreboard ticking and played some aggressive shots. Marnus Labuschagne brought up his half-century whereas David Warner is close to getting his half-century after his reprieve. The duo have done well to remain unscathed till Lunch and Australia look well on course to post a healthy first innings lead.

Definitely Australia's session! David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne have brought up a 100-run stand between them and have done well to bat this session out.
