Angles this one on middle. Marnus Labuschagne watchfully defends it.
Outside off delivery, on a length. Marnus Labuschagne with yet another leave.
A length ball, way outside off. Marnus Labuschagne shoulders arms to it.
A length ball, on off, defended back on the deck.
A full ball, straight on middle. David Warner pushes it nicely straight down the ground before the fielder cuts it off. Three taken.
Length and on middle. Marnus Labuschagne tucks it to mid-wicket.
Quick single! A length ball, on middle. Warner taps it in front of covers and scampers through for a single.
Swing and a miss! Short of a length, outside off. Warner looks to cut it again but misses it completely.
Body blow! A length ball, angling on middle. David Warner rocks back as he looks to flick but gets beaten by the pace. Gets hit on the body.
On middle, on a length. Blocked out.
Wood continues from 'round the wicket and serves a length ball, just around off. Warner tries to cut it but this was too close to cut.
Fuller in length, on off. Marnus Labuschagne defends it towards point. He calls for a single and starts running but David Warner sends him back and rightly so. A maiden over from Woakes!
Short of a length, on off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone.
Length ball, on middle. Pushed back to the bowler.
Good-length ball, coming into the batter, on leg. Marnus Labuschagne looks to tuck but gets hit on the pads. An appeal from the keeper for an lbw but the umpire says no. Probably going down leg.
In the corridor of uncertainty, no swing this time. Marnus Labuschagne lets it through.
Good-length ball, around off, nipping in. Marnus Labuschagne makes a good leave.
Chris Woakes (3-0-9-0) is back into the attack as he replaces Ollie Robinson.
Swing and a miss! Good-length ball, well outside off. David Warner goes chasing for it and has a hard swing at it but fails to connect. A maiden!
Good-length ball, on middle, angling in. David Warner pushes it to point.
Good bouncer from Wood! Bangs a short ball, hard onto the deck, on middle. David Warner sits under it.
Length ball, outside off. Warner pushes it straight to point.
On a length, on off. David Warner taps it to point.
Just short! Back of a length, on off. David Warner chips it uppishly towards extra cover. The ball falls just short of Ben Stokes there.
FOUR! Shot! Fuller in length, on off, at 130 clicks. Marnus Labuschagne this time drives it past mid off. Ben Stokes gives it a chase but the ball wins the race to the boundary.
Touch fuller, on off. Marnus Labuschagne drives it towards covers.
Back of a length, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone.

FOUR! Good-length ball, around off. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend. The ball goes off the outside edge and races past the slip cordon to third man for a boundary. Few words exchanged between them.

Fuller in length, on the pads. David Warner flicks it to mid-wicket for a tight single. Chris Woakes quickly moves to his left, picks the ball and has a shy at the striker's end but misses. The batsman was well in though.
Good-length ball, angling away from off. David Warner shoulders arms to it.
This is a little fuller, in the corridor of uncertainty. Marnus Labuschagne is not interested in playing that. Just a single off the over then.
Length ball, outside off, at 151.6 kph. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it for the keeper to collect.
Good-length delivery, around off, at 150 kph. Marnus Labuschagne watches the ball closely and leaves it untouched.
Some serious pace there from Wood! Short of a length, on middle, at 147.2 kph. Marnus Labuschagne blocks it onto the deck.
Short of a length again, on middle. David Warner hops and taps it to the off side for a single.
Short of a length from around the wicket, outside off. David Warner offers no shot to that.
Mark Wood is into the attack now.
Ohh, that was close! Full again, very close to the off stump. Marnus Labuschagne at first thinks of playing it but in the end, opts out as he shoulders arms.
Pitched up, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne lets it sail through.
Fuller in length, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne drills it to point.
Good-length ball, around off. Got some extra bounce as well. Marnus Labuschagne moves away and lets it through.
Marnus Labuschagne walks in at number 3.

OUT! CAUGHT! England needed an early breakthrough and Ollie Robinson provides them with one. Hurls a good-length ball, outside off, nipping away. Marcus Harris has a feel for it. The ball kisses the outside edge and flies to the third slip. Dawid Malan moves to his left and takes a good low catch. Ollie Robinson roars as he draws first blood. Good start by them and Marcus Harris has to walk back to the pavilion for a timid score.
Commentary.Howout: c Dawid Malan b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Good-length ball, in the fourth stump channel. Marcus Harris shoulders arms.
Dot to end the over! On a length, on middle. Warner blocks it on the deck.
Short of a length, outside off. David Warner leaves it alone to the keeper.
Short and on middle. Warner with another good leave as he leans back and lets it through to the keeper.
Way outside off, on a length. Left alone.
Short and outside off. Warner sways away from it.
FOUR! The sound it made when the ball hit the blade. Brilliant. A length ball, outside off. David Warner drives it firmly through mid off for a boundary. Helds his pose as well.
BEATEN! Good finish to the over. This is on a length and just around the 4th stump channel. Harris has a poke at it but misses as the ball whizzes past the outside edge.
Change of bats for David Warner.
Robinson concedes his first run. A full ball, on middle. Warner punches it with soft hands to mid off and scampers across for a quick single.
On a length and on middle. Warner hangs back and punches it back to the bowler.
Outside off again, on a length. Warner steps across and shoulders arms to it.
A length ball, straight and on middle. David Warner solidly blocks it out.
Length ball but this is way outside off. Easy leave for Warner.
Short of a length, outside off, extra bounce on offer. Harris lets it through to the keeper.
Another leave from Harris as he prods across and shoulders arms to this full ball.
Length ball, outside off. Positive leave from Marcus Harris.
Full and on the pads, flicked to the left of mid-wicket where the fielder dives and stops it. A single.
A length ball, on middle. Warner prods and defends it back to the bowler. Chris Woakes collects the ball and mimes a throw as Warner is made to race back to the crease.
JAFFA! Woakes goes fuller now, outside off. Warner does not move too much as he tries to defend it. Gets beaten on the outside edge.
Length and on middle. Harris blocks it back to the bowler. Maiden to start for Ollie Robinson.
On a length, outside off. Harris covers his stumps and shoulders arms to it.
BEATEN! Good bowling from Robinson. This one jags away after landing, Harris is squared up as he looks to defend it out.
Touch fuller, on middle. Harris defends it off the front foot to covers.
A length ball, on off. Harris works it with an angled bat to gully.

Robinson starts with a length ball, angling outside off. Harris looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge. Only the slip cordon is appealing for a caught behind but Ollie Robinson shakes his head.
Ollie Robinson to bowl from the other end.
On a length, on off. Harris punches it through point for a single. Both Australian openers off to a confident start.
Now targets the hip area. Harris stays back and tries to nudge it away. Gets hit on the body though. No swing or seam noticed yet.
Marcus Harris is off the mark as well! A length ball, outside off. Harris leans into his drive and hits it through covers for a brace. Confident-looking drive that from Harris!
Short again and on middle. Harris stands behind the line of the ball and defends it on the surface.
Short of a length, on middle. Harris stands tall and blocks it out. Good bounce from Woakes.
Australia and David Warner are underway. A length ball, on off. Warner taps it to point and runs for a quick single. The fielder has a shy at the bowler's end but instead hits it to Warner.

We're back. The players are also back on the field. 20 runs to get for Australia for the series lead. Alex Carey and Marcus Harris will open and they would love to have a 10-wicket victory. Can they do it? Ollie Robinson to bowl the first over.
...FINAL INNINGS...

77 runs and 8 wickets in the morning session and England have ended up spoiling all the good work done on Day 3. It's a surrender from their batsmen and Australia should be commended for showing character. All their genuine bowlers contributed with Nathan Lyon finishing with four wickets. Do join us in a short while after the Lunch break for the final rites.

Nathan Lyon is leading Australia off the park! He completed his 400 Test wickets this morning and his breakthrough provided Australia with an early opening. The morning session has entirely belonged to the hosts. After some amazing work from the pair of Joe Root and Dawid Malan on Day 3, the Aussie bowlers bounced back and put a spirited performance. Nathan Lyon struck early to remove Malan and soon Joe Root and Ollie Pope also fell. Jos Buttler and Ben Stokes spent some time in the middle to build a partnership but then they also punched in the return ticket to the pavilion. The English tail didn't wag once again and they are now on the brink of losing this Test match.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Superb delivery, Green follows the batsman with a well-directed short ball at 138.3 kph, Woakes leans back and attempts to play the upper-cut but only manages to edge it to Alex Carey. He claims his 8th catch of this Test match. What a debut for him! He equals Brian Taber and Chris Read who also had eight wicket-keeping dismissals on Test debut. England are bundled out for 297 with a lead of only 19 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Carey b Cameron Green

Commentary.Commentary: Fuller and on off, slanting in, Woakes defends it from the back foot to the off side.
Around middle and leg, on a length, Woakes keeps it out to mid-wicket.
On a length around off, Chris pushes it with soft hands to cover-point.
Back of a length around off, Woakes pushes it from the back foot to the off side.
Gets behind the line of the delivery and taps it down to square leg.
Wide! A gentle bouncer and it has gone way over the head of the batsman. Called a wide for height.
Cameron Green (11-3-22-1) comes back to bowl.
Beaten! Drift again for Lyne, he lands it just outside off and gets it to skid in, a late decision by Leach to cut but he misses.
Spinning away from around off, Leach lets it through to the keeper.
Jack Leach is the last man in. This session will be extended now with England nine down.

OUT! TIMBER! A classic off spinner to dismiss Mark Wood. A generously tossed up delivery around off, plenty of drift on this one as it lands full and around off, Wood is lured into the drive but it beats the outside half of his bat and goes on to tickle the off pole. Lyon has a 4-fer now and England one wicket away from getting bundled out. They are ahead by just 18 runs.
Commentary.Howout: b Nathan Lyon

Commentary.Commentary: Flighted and on off, defended from the crease by Wood.
Loopy and around off, turning back in, Woakes tries to defend off the front foot but it takes the inside edge and rolls wide of short leg. They cross.
Full and floated, around off and spinning in, Woakes defends it with his bat in front of his front pad.
Yet another bouncer, slightly wayward this time as it's angling down the leg side, Wood has a comfortable leave on this occasion.
Bouncer, nicely directed this time, around middle and leg, Wood immediately takes cover and ducks.
Fuller and around off, driven through the line to mid off.
FOUR! Wood has decided to fight fire with fire. Short in length again but there is some width offered outside off, Wood stays back and ramps it down to third man for a boundary.
That's a rip-roaring bouncer. Starc clocks 142.3 kph and dishes out a nasty bouncer around middle, it's well-directed, Wood fails to move away from the line of fire and takes a blow on his gloves.
Starc steams in from 'round the wicket and hurls a length ball outside off at 142.7 clicks, Wood sits back and plays a mistimed shot to the off side.
Tossed up, on a length, around middle. Mark Wood presses forward to block but it goes off the inside edge past the short leg fielder.
Shorter in length, around middle, Mark Wood blocks it watchfully.
Flatter and quicker, around middle, Chris Woakes sits back and eases it past the diving mid on fielder to collect a single.
Loopy ball, way outside off. Chris Woakes defends it to covers.
Flatter ball, outside off. Chris Woakes blocks it.
Tossed up, on a length, outside off. Chris Woakes defends it out.
A bouncer, around middle. Mark Wood gets behind the line and keeps it out. The ball pops out but falls well short of the short leg fielder.
Back of a length, outside off. Chris Woakes stays back and steers it behind square on the off side for a run.
Short of a length, on middle. Chris Woakes gets behind the line to block.
Good-length ball, outside off. Chris Woakes drives hard but Travis Head at covers dives to his left and stops the ball.
Banged into the deck, around leg. Mark Wood looks to block but it goes off his gloves behind square on the leg side for a single.
Full ball, outside off. Chris Woakes looks to play the cover drive but it goes off the inside edge past the leg stump and the batters sneak in a run.
Flatter ball, around off. Mark Wood defends it off the back foot.
Mark Wood walks out to bat.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ollie Robinson tries to get creative but he perishes in doing so! Lyon cleverly tosses this one up, outside off. Robinson looks to play the reverse sweep but does not nail it and hits it straight to Travis Head at backward point who takes a good sharp catch. England lose another and they lead by just 8 runs in the second innings.
Commentary.Howout: c Travis Head b Nathan Lyon

Commentary.Commentary: Flatter and quicker, around off. Chris Woakes eases it to long on for a single.
Flatter ball, outside off and spinning in late. Chris Woakes blocks it off the back foot.
Tossed up, around off. Ollie Robinson shimmies down to slog but it goes off the thick inside edge past the short fine leg fielder. Mitchell Starc gives it a chase and the batters take three runs.
Tossed up, around off. Ollie Robinson defends it out.
Swing and a miss! A length ball, outside off and angling away with the arm of the bowler. Chris Woakes looks to drive on the up but he misses as the ball zips past the outside edge.
A well-directed bouncer, around leg. Chris Woakes dabs it into the deck.
Banged into the pitch, outside off. Chris Woakes leaves it alone.
Length ball, angling in from middle, Chris Woakes presses forward and blocks it out.
Length ball, outside off. Chris Woakes reaches out and looks for a booming drive but it goes off the inner half of the bat back to the bowler.
Full ball, outside off. Ollie Robinson hangs back and drives it past the mid off fielder. The fielder at mid off gives it a chase and the batters take three runs.
Mitchell Starc is back on.
Slightly shorter in length, around middle and turning in late. Chris Woakes drops it in front of short leg.
Lyon spills this one down leg. Chris Woakes lets it be and Alex Carey moves across to his left to gather the ball.
Another ball, flatter and quicker, around off. Chris Woakes keeps it out.
Flatter and quicker, around middle, Chris Woakes pushes it to mid-wicket.
Tossed up, on a fuller length, around off. Ollie Robinson skips down to slog but it goes off the inner half of the blade towards deep mid-wicket for a run. England lead by 1 run now!
Flatter and quicker, around middle, Ollie Robinson blocks it out.
Nathan Lyon is back on. 2 for 83 in his 30 overs. In his first spell this morning, he got his much-awaited 400th Test scalp by dismissing Dawid Malan.
Cummins hurls a well-directed bumper, around off. Chris Woakes ducks under it at first then tries to ramp it over the keeper but he misses.
Good-length ball, on off. Chris Woakes pushes it to mid off.

FOUR! Edged, but safe! Good-length ball, just outside off. Chris Woakes looks to push inside the line but gets a genuine outside edge which goes in between the gully and second slip fielders for a boundary. England have cut down the deficit and are effectively 0 for 7.
Short of a length, outside off. Chris Woakes hangs back and opens the face of his bat to steer it away from the slip cordon but he finds the gully fielder.
Back of a length, around off. Chris Woakes sits back and blocks it towards covers.
Banged in into the deck, just outside off. Chris Woakes tried fending it off but missed.
A well-directed bumper, around middle. Ollie Robinson backs away and sways away from the line of fire by taking his eyes off the ball.
Good-length ball, angling in from middle. Ollie Robinson defends it out.

Full ball, around middle. Chris Woakes plays the on drive but Pat Cummins puts in a dive at mid on to save a certain boundary. Since it's not a clean stop as the ball wobbles out of his hands, the batsmen get the chance to take a single.
Hazlewood goes full this time, outside off. Woakes pushes it to mid off, off the back foot.
Back of a length, around middle, Chris Woakes defends it to mid on.
Good-length ball, around off. Chris Woakes looks to defend but it goes off the outside edge towards the gully fielder, on the bounce.
Good-length ball, around off. Ollie Robinson blocks it out.

Top delivery! A length ball, jagging back in from outside off. Ollie Robinson looks to defend but the ball sneaks through his defense and brushes his back pad before going to the keeper. Alex Carey collects the ball, appeals but the umpire shakes his head.
A well-directed bumper, around off. Ollie Robinson ducks yet again.
Funny! Full ball, outside off. Ollie Robinson anticipates a bumper so he thinks of ducking underneath first and leaves it alone in the end. Very awkward.
Sharp bounce! Short of a length, outside off. Ollie Robinson looks to block but it hits the shoulder of his bat and rolls towards the gully fielder.
Cummins bends his back and bangs it into the deck, around middle. Ollie Robinson ducks underneath.
Length ball, angling in from outside off. Chris Woakes leaves it alone.
FOUR! Nicely done! Back of a length, around off. Chris Woakes stays back, rides the bounce well and steers it past the point fielder to collect a boundary. The deficit is 5 now.
Short of a length, outside off. Ollie Robinson stays back and taps it to the right of the gully fielder. Cameron Green there dives across to his right and stops the ball. A single taken.
BEATEN! Back of a length, just outside off, shaping away a bit and bouncing off the deck. Ollie Robinson looks to have a tentative push but he misses as the ball whistles past his blade.
Length ball, angling in from middle. Ollie Robinson defends it towards mid on.
Ollie Robinson is the new batsman.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Oh, dear! Nothing has gone England's way this morning and Australia are bossing this game! Hazlewood serves a good-length ball, outside off, shaping away a hint off the seam. Buttler has a needless poke at it away from his body and it takes the outside edge towards Alex Carey behind the sticks who takes a simple catch, his 7th in this Test match so far. England lose their seventh wicket and they still trail by 10 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Carey b Josh Hazlewood

Commentary.Commentary: Good-length ball, around off. Chris Woakes blocks it out towards covers.
Back of a length, outside off. Chris Woakes stays back to block it but it goes off the outer half of the blade past the gully fielder. The batters take a couple of runs.
Short and down the leg side, Woakes tries glancing but misses. A terrific take by Alex Carey.
Edged but safe! On a length and outside off, Woakes has a poke at it and edges it behind towards gully. It doesn't carry and Green does well to stop it with a dive to his left.
Length ball, around off. Chris Woakes blocks it out.

Was there any bat on it? Was it too high? Cummins consults his mates for the DRS and decides to go against it. A good-length ball, around off and nipping back in sharply. Chris Woakes is stuck in his crease as he tries to block it but he misses and gets hit high on his pad. Cummins appeals but the umpire says no. The Hawk Eye confirms that the ball would have gone over the sticks. The good thing about Pat Cummins is that he considers a few facts before deciding to use the review, unlike a few others.
On a good length around off, Jos sticks on the back foot and defends it with soft hands to point.
This one is darted in, on a length and around off, Buttler covers the angle and defends it back.
Almost edges it behind! That's a terrific delivery. Josh Hazlewood probes around the off stump area and it skids on with the angle with some extra bounce, Buttler pokes at it and misses.
In the zone outside off, short in length, Buttler restrains himself from going after the width.
Gets behind the line of the delivery and offers a dead straight bat in defense.
Back of a length, around off and angling in, Buttler defends it from the back foot.
Cummins digs in a bouncer, Woakes ducks. End of a successful over for the Aussie skipper.
The batsman has just blocked that from his crease.
Chris Woakes is the new man in at number 8.

OUT! That's a snorter and Pat Cummins has taken out Ben Stokes. The sixth wicket goes down for England and they still trail by 12 runs. Once again the extra bounce that Cummins generates has done the trick. He is a beast with the new ball. Lands it around leg and gets it to jump a tad extra off the deck. Stokes is squared up slightly in his stance as he tries to work it on the leg side but closes the face of his bat early. The ball lobs off the leading edge and Cameron Green grabs the catch safely at gully. The replays show that it took the shoulder of his bat. The Aussies are ecstatic, England's talisman is gone.
Commentary.Howout: c Cameron Green b Pat Cummins

Commentary.Commentary: Arrows a length ball around off, angling away, Stokes stays on the back foot and defends it very late near his body.
Extra bounce again, around middle and leg, Buttler leaps on the back foot and tucks it down to fine leg for a single.
Cummins hits the deck hard and immediately gets some extra lift. Around off and Buttler does well to defend it down.
Pat Cummins (16-5-44-1) brings himself into the attack.
Angling away from the batsman, around off and moving away slightly, Stokes guards his stumps and shoulders arms.
Josh Hazlewood goes fuller this time, around middle and off, Buttler takes a couple of steps down the track and defends it to mid off.
Bowls it a touch short and keeps it close to off, Stokes remains on the back foot and defends it down.
Sliding down the leg side, on a length, Jos tucks it towards long leg and rotates the strike.
On a good length, around off and angling in, Buttler defends it from the back foot.

FOUR! Well timed and placed. Josh Hazlewood overpitches outside off, Jos Buttler leans into the drive and caresses it square of the wicket on the off side. Nathan Lyon chases from point but to no avail.

DRINKS! So far, it has been Australia's morning as they have come back strongly on Day 4 and they would be extremely pleased to see both the overnight batters back in the pavilion along with Ollie Pope. Ben Stokes and Jos Buttler need a big partnership here if England are to have any chances in this game.
Back of a length, on middle, worked to mid-wicket.
On a length and outside off, played down to point.
Shortish, targeting the body, Stokes tries to fend but misses. It goes off his pads to short leg.
Play and a miss! Full and outside off, Ben Stokes is beaten while attempting to drive.
A touch short and on off, defended down to gully.
Outside off, no shot offered.
FOUR! Length ball, outside off, steered through backward point for a boundary.
Beaten! Buttler tries driving off the front foot but misses.
Outside off, defended to point.
Presses forward and works it with the angle of the bowler to mid-wicket.
FOUR! Edged! Buttler tries defending off the front foot but it takes the outside edge and finds the gap between the slip cordon and gully.
Shortish, outside off, shaping away, Buttler leaves.
Outside off, on a length, Ben makes another leave.
A touch short and outside off, left alone.
On the pads, helped wide of mid on for one.
Pitches it up and around off, Jos pushes it off his front foot to mid off.
A lifter, striking Stokes on his gloves as he attempts to glance. It rolls behind square leg and they cross.
Outside off, left alone.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.
Extra bounce, Buttler tries to fend it away but it goes off the thigh pad to gully.
Uses the angle of the bowler and works it gently to mid-wicket.
Angling in and hitting Buttler on the pads. It deflects to gully.
A touch short and outside off, not much movement, Buttler once again gives it the silent treatment by leaving it alone.
In the channel outside off, Buttler shoulders arms.
Josh Hazlewood (8-4-13-0) comes into the attack now.
FOUR! Boom! Width on offer, full in length, Stokes latches onto it and smashes it through covers for a boundary. The deficit is below 30 runs now.
Back of a length, outside off and shaping away, Stokes allows it through.
Fullish and on off, driven off the front foot to mid off.
Starc goes fuller and lands it outside off, Stokes attempts to drive but misses.
Back of a length around off, Stokes pushes at it and misses.
Starts with a fuller one, shaping in, Buttler helps it to square leg for a single.
The second new ball has been taken. Mitchell Starc to use it first.
Presses forward to a full ball and defends it with soft hands to silly point.
Tossed up and outside off, left alone.
Gets forward to a full ball and defends it to silly point.
Tossed up and around off, Stokes stays back and defends it to the off side.
FOUR! Bang! Loopy and full around off, Stokes goes down on one knee and sweeps it well in front of square leg for a cracking boundary.
Flighted and full, around off, Jos Buttler is not shying away from playing the reverse-batted shot. Connects and sends it through backward point for a single.
Green switches to 'round the wicket and hurls across a length ball wide outside off, an easy leave for Stokes.
Plays late and plays well. Around off on a length, moving away a bit, Jos plays close to his body and eases it with an angled bat to cover-point for one.
Pitches it up and close to off, Buttler is forward with a straight bat and pushes it down to mid on.
A touch short and on off, Jos pushes it from the back foot to covers.

Beaten all ends up! This is the reason Australia have not opted for the second new ball. Green is getting the old one to move around. A gentle outswinger, landing around off and shaping away a bit, Jos Buttler feels for it and gets beaten.
Gets behind the line of the delivery and defends it to the off side.
The second new ball is due now. Will Australia take it? Nopes. They are not taking it. Cameron Green will continue...
Fuller in length, outside off. Ben Stokes prods and pushes it to covers.
Loopy ball, outside off. Ben Stokes gets forward and keeps it out.
Tossed up, on a fuller length, outside off. Ben Stokes blocks it out.
Flatter ball, shorter in length, around off. Jos Buttler waits for the ball to turn and tucks it wide of mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! Intent from Jos Buttler! This is tossed up, outside off. Buttler gets forward and reverse-sweeps it past the backward point fielder to collect a boundary. He is off the mark in some style.
Flatter ball, on a length, around off. Jos Buttler stays back to defend but it goes off the outer half of the blade towards backward point.
Back of a length, outside off and nipping back in slightly. Ben Stokes lets it through to the keeper.
A yorker, around off. Stokes gets his bat down in time and digs it out.
Sloppy from the cover fielder but no harm done! Full ball, outside off. Ben Stokes drives it to the cover fielder who fumbles but Stokes does not go for a single.
Short of a length, angling in from outside off. Ben Stokes leaves it alone.
Back of a length, just outside off. Stokes hangs back and lets it through to the keeper.
Full ball, outside off. Ben Stokes prods but shoulders arms to this one.
Flatter ball, outside off, going on with the angle. Buttler stays back to block but it beats the outside edge.
Fuller in length, outside off. Jos Buttler defends it out towards cover.
Flatter and quicker, around off. Jos Buttler hangs back and blocks it out.
Jos Buttler walks in next with England staring down the barrel. Nathan Lyon has his tail up now...

OUT! CAUGHT! What is happening here? England lose another and they have lost their third wicket in the space of just 14 runs this morning! With the monkey off his back, Nathan Lyon is bowling with a nice rhythm. Gives this one some extra toss and lands it close to off, it has got good revs and there is an excellent grip for him as the ball lands and turns in with some extra bounce. Pope stays back and looks to cut but the bounce gets big on his bat and it takes the shoulder of his blade before hurrying to Steven Smith at first slip. He takes a sharp catch by stretching to his right and Australia are smelling blood.
Commentary.Howout: c Steven Smith b Nathan Lyon

Commentary.Commentary: Flatter ball, outside off. Stokes punches it to the cover-point fielder who half-stops it and the batters collect a single.
Tossed up, on off. Ben Stokes blocks it out.

OUT! CAUGHT! Finally! Finally! Nathan Lyon has scaled the mountain of 400 wickets in Test cricket, it has been an arduous climb, to be honest, as Lyon had to spend extra time in preying that elusive one wicket. He is only behind two greats, Shane Warne and Glenn McGrath, in the list of the leading wicket-takers for Australia in Test cricket. From being a pitch curator at the Adelaide Oval to becoming only the 7th spinner in Test cricket history to do so after the famous six - Muttiah Muralitharan, Shane Warne, Anil Kumble, Rangana Herath, Harbhajan Singh and Ravichandran Ashwin, it's been one heck of a ride. Now coming to the delivery, it's nicely flighted and around off, Dawid Malan takes a step down the track and tries to flick but gets an inside edge onto the pads. It lobs up and Marnus Labuschagne reacts quickly from silly point to catch the ball. They all appeal and the finger has gone up. Something similar happened on the second ball of this over as well but then Dawid escaped. Not this time. Early exit for him this morning and it's a perfect start for Australia. 326 days between 399 and 400 wickets. That was a long wait. Lyon takes the ball and shows it to the audience to celebrate his milestone. Take a bow, GOAT!
Commentary.Howout: c Marnus Labuschagne b Nathan Lyon

Just in - It's official!!! The fifth Ashes Test is heading to Hobart as a day-night series finale, confirms the official Twitter handle of Australia.

The Aussies dominated the first two days of the Test but Day 3, which is considered to be a moving day in Test cricket belonged to England. The Australian bowlers gave it their all but ended the day with just 2 wickets and would be a touch disappointed, especially after a terrific performance in the first innings. Pat Cummins tried six different bowlers but England's batters showed a huge amount of grit and determination. Nathan Lyon continued his hunt for his 400th Test wicket and he seemed nowhere close to his best. Their pace bowlers will need to bring their A-game on Day 4 and the good thing for them is that the new ball is due in 10 overs. Cummins and company would be keen to take full advantage of this red cherry and make early inroads in the first session. All to play for in the first Ashes Test as all three results are still possible and it promises to be another exciting day of Test cricket.

England have made a roaring comeback into this Test match after conceding a lead of 278 runs in the first innings. Earlier on Day 3, the English bowlers bowled out Australia for 425 and once again found themselves in a spot of bother at 61/2 in their second innings. It was England's skipper, Joe Root and Dawid Malan who dug deep and ensured that they did not lose any more wickets. They now trail by 58 runs and the first session on Day 4 is going to be extremely vital for both teams. Root and Malan's first target of the day would be to cut the deficit without losing any wickets and then score as many runs as possible. All eyes would be on the No.1 ranked Test batter, Joe Root, who would be eyeing his first Test hundred on Australian soil.

Hello and a warm welcome to the coverage of Day 4 of the first Ashes Test which is being played at the iconic Gabba. Day 3 saw England fighting it out, led by their skipper Joe Root who looked rock-solid in the middle. Dawid Malan also got his act together and both these classy players have put on an unbeaten partnership of 159 runs, making sure that England stay in the contest against the mighty Aussies, at home. The Aussie bowlers toiled hard on Day 3 but the visitors showed great resistance and we are in for an enthralling fourth day of this Ashes Test.
...DAY 4, SESSION 1...

What can we expect over the weekend? Friday started as possibly being the last day of this Test. Now, we could well be in a position to have another 5 sessions of cricket, though a couple of early wickets might just change that. This match hangs nicely in the balance. Who will wrestle the control? The first ball on Day 4 will be bowled at 9.30 am local (2330 GMT, previous day), but as usual, the buildup will begin well in advance. Do join us then, for all the action on Saturday, 11th December, 2021. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

Dawid Malan and Joe Root were extremely patient early on and then started to up the ante, attacking the likes of Lyon and Green. Both survived some nervous moments in the last half hour of play but are still unseparated, having stitched a partnership of 159. Australia bowled in decent lines and lengths but this pitch seems to have gotten quicker and apart from that, there looks to be nothing much on the deck. Also, the Aussie bowlers looked a bit tired with the sun staying out the whole day. However, all these are expected in a good Test match played between balanced teams. Cummins will know that, in spite of this being his first real test of captaincy. He had his bowlers around for a pep talk but applauded everyone for their efforts. Saturday will be a new day and a fresh start will be expected from them on Day 4. Australia will still believe that if they can knock two wickets quickly in the opening hour, who knows, they might come back strongly in this game.

The day began with Australia having 3 wickets in their bank and leading by 196. England would have hoped to finish off the tail quickly but Starc hung around with Head to push Australia beyond 400. Eventually, when the visitors did manage to get the Aussies all done, the deficit read 278. They began their second dig on a rough note too, losing Burns early yet again. But after that, Hameed and Malan dug in, frustrating the Kangaroos. Hameed lost his concentration and his wicket but since then, it has all been Malan and Root.

Lots of oohhs and aahs from the 'Gabba crowd as that final ball was bowled. Did Joe nick it? Was there an edge? Naah.... everything's settled and that caps a fantastic day for England in this opening Test of the 2021-22 Ashes. What a phenomenal comeback. Starting the innings being 278 behind, they have now got themselves in a position of balance, trailing by just 58 now and having 8 wickets in the bank. Another tough day for the bowlers, but this time, the Aussies were at the receiving end.

The final sessions in Australia usually bring a lot of runs. And sometimes, wickets too. If England just hang in there for a while, this could be a big session in terms of runs and we could have this Test right back in the balance. 39 overs are left in the day, so potentially around 125-130 runs can be scored. Do join us at 3 pm local (0500 GMT) for the final session to find out.

Australia will not be too disappointed with their efforts. On another hot and humid day, the fast bowlers have given it their all, minus Starc. Not surprising, is it? The great Shane Warne had already predicted on Thursday that Starc usually struggles in the second innings if he does well in the first and that is what happened. Pat Cummins continues to lead from the front while Hazlewood continues to be probing. Meanwhile, Nathan Lyon is still searching for his 400th Test wicket. Will he get to the milestone? As of now, Cummins has not been forced to bring on his 5th bowler but if another 30 minutes pass by without a wicket, Cameron Green will be given the ball and that is the time to attack, as Australia did in the evening of Day 2.

Sometimes, wearing down the opposition works well. Australia started the session post Lunch strongly, getting two wickets but then Malan and Root just stood strong. They struggled for a little bit but ensured that they did not throw their wicket away. And eventually, a few loose deliveries allowed the England batters some scoring opportunities. The visitors need their skipper and Dawid Malan to bat throughout the final session to ensure that the vigil brings a good result.

Well, 30 runs came in the last 6 overs, thanks to some counterattack from Malan and Root but the visitors have an almighty mountain to climb. They have clung on towards the end of this session but you feel they will require a bit more if they are to sustain as they still trail by 171 runs.

The lure, magic and desperation of 400 - We all know that Nathan Lyon has been stuck on 399 Test wickets for quite a while now. Who better than the King Of Spin to talk about spin? Shane Warne digresses the way the GOAT has been bowling in the last few innings. Warney reckons that usually, Lyon lures the batter in flight, makes him come forward and varies his speed well. But because he is overeager to get to that milestone of 400, the flight has lessened and Lyon's greatest strength - accuracy - is deserting him. Warne adds that if Lyon can just be patient, as he otherwise normally is, number 400 will come. It is not a matter of will, just a matter of when.

That concludes the proceedings from the Gabba Test. Australia have taken an early lead in the series and also pocketed 12 crucial points in the ICC World Test Championship. Adelaide Oval will host the second Ashes Test (day-night), starting on Thursday, 16th December 2021. The first ball will be at 2.30 pm local (4 am GMT) but you can join us in advance for the build-up. Cheers!

TRAVIS HEAD IS THE MAN OF THE MATCH! Says that the support staff and Pat Cummins gave him the clarity and it's great to contribute. Feels it's a great starting point for them as a team. Adds that the stand of David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne set him up and he took a lot from the way Jos Buttler batted. Talking about his hundred and celebration, Travis replies that the emotions were high and he loved every moment of it. On Nathan Lyon picking up his 400th Test wicket, Head is all praise for the off spinner and says that he came back beautifully and stayed tough. Head is looking forward to returning home and playing a Test match in Adelaide.

Pat Cummins, the victorious captain of Australia, says that he really enjoyed the experience of leading the team and feels that a lot of things went right for him, right from the toss. He is very proud of everyone and considers it to be a complete performance. Appreciates the partnership between David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne and also praises the knock of Travis Head. Tells that during England's fightback on Day 3, Australia bowled without much luck and he was happy to see that everyone was positive and didn't think too much apart from getting the breakthroughs. Regarding Travis Head, Cummins replies that's why they want him in the side as he can take the game away in quick time. Further says that Head has a bright future ahead. On Josh Hazlewood not bowling much on Day 3, Cummins informs that he was a little bit sore, so they didn't want him to break as this is a long Test series. Regarding the fitness of David Warner, Pat tells that he has pulled up well and will be good to go for Adelaide.

Joe Root, the skipper of England, starts by admitting that it's frustrating as they worked really hard to get themselves back in the game. Adds that they knew it was important to try and get through the second new ball safely but they failed to get past the initial period. Mentions that the pitch had sideways movement and the cracks were also visible and it's a shame they didn't put up a fight with the bat. On his decision to bat first, Root replies by saying that it's easy to look at things in hindsight and adds that they have variations in their bowling attack to navigate through different gears. Root points out that they didn't start well with the bat and tells that they know where they need to improve. Wants his team to relish the challenge to go out there and get one back. Talks about the positives and says that the bowling effort was commendable. Signs off by saying that they need to learn from this experience and come back stronger.
Presentation time...

A fruitful captaincy debut for Pat Cummins! He picked up a fifer on Day 1 to set the tone for this Ashes and the knocks of David Warner, Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head made sure that Australia build on the start provided by their bowlers. There were minor hiccups but the Australian lower order stuck around to form crucial partnerships and in a way that turned out to be the difference between the two sides. After gaining a hefty lead and also picking a couple of early English wickets, Australia were put to a stern test on Day 3, once the ball got old, but they showed great character to bounce back and seal the deal.

One swallow doesn't make a summer! After scoring just 147 runs in the first innings and conceding a lead of 278 runs, one big partnership was never going to be enough for England. Joe Root and Dawid Malan showed great grit and determination to keep Australia at bay on the third day but things unravelled rather too quickly this morning. Nathan Lyon's much-awaited 400th Test wicket arrived in the shape of Dawid Malan's wicket early on Day 4 and from there on the English innings went downhill.

That's an emphatic win for Australia to take the lead in the series. They will be very satisfied with their overall performance in this Test match. After losing against India last time around, the Aussies have redeemed themselves at a venue famously known as the Gabbatoir.

Good-length delivery, angling in from middle. Alex Carey tucks it wide of mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Back of a length, around middle. Alex Carey nudges it towards mid-wicket.
On a length, around off. Alex Carey prods to block this one out.
Back of a length, around middle. Alex Carey tucks it to mid-wicket.
Length ball, outside off and staying a touch low. Alex Carey looks to block but he misses.

Run out chance missed! Good-length ball, way outside off. Alex Carey lifts it over the cover region. Haseeb Hameed, at covers, gives it a chase and stops the ball by sliding just in front of the fence. The batters take three runs. Carey wants three and would have been a goner had Ollie Robinson collected the throw from the deep cleanly.
Good-length ball, on off. Alex Carey defends it off the front foot.
Length ball, around off. Alex Carey pushes it to mid off.
Full ball, around leg. Marcus Harris clips it to fine leg for a single.
Back of a length, outside off and angling away late. Marcus Harris shoulders arms to this one. No ball signalled by the umpire as Ollie Robinson oversteps.
Good-length ball, outside off. Marcus Harris leaves it alone.
Length ball, on off. Alex Carey taps it to covers and takes off for a run. Haseeb Hameed at cover-point collects the ball and has a shy at the non-striker's end but he misses.
Back of a length, outside off. Marcus Harris leaves it alone.
Time for the DRS. An lbw appeal against Marcus Harris has not been entertained by the umpire and Joe Root has decided to review it. Hot Spot detects a mark on the bat.

NOT OUT! An inside edge saves Marcus Harris! Length ball, pitching around middle and nipping back in slightly. Harris looks to defend but fails to do so cleanly. He is rapped on the pads, they appeal but the finger stays down. Joe Root decides to review it but the Hot Spot detects a spot on the bat.
Woakes hurls a good-length ball, around leg. Carey stays back and glances it to the left of the fine leg fielder. Ollie Robinson there cuts it off and the batters take a run.
Good-length ball, around off and angling in just that little but. Alex Carey keeps it out.
Back of a length, around leg. Alex Carey looks to tuck it to the leg side but he misses and gets hit high on his body.
Woakes starts with a length ball, around middle, Alex Carey presses forward and defends it solidly.
Chris Woakes to speed in from the opposite end.
Length ball, on off. Alex Carey looks to defend but gets a thick inside edge behind square on the leg side. The batters cross for a single. Carey gets off the mark.
JAFFA! Good-length ball, pitching around off and curling away sharply. Carey sits back and looks to drive but he misses as the ball goes past the outside edge.
Short of a length, way outside off and angling away late. Alex Carey does not offer any shot to this one.
On a length, around off. Alex Carey gets behind the line of the ball to block it.
Back of a length, way outside off. Alex Carey prods and shoulders arms to this one.
Good-length ball, outside off and shaping away a bit. Alex Carey looks to poke at it but the ball goes past the outside edge.
NO BALL! Robinson starts with a good-length ball, on off, Alex Carey blocks it to covers and looks for a run but is sent back by Marcus Harris. Robinson oversteps and the umpire signals a no ball.
